Whine & Dine 

Colored pencils and WSJ newspaper, 
24” x 36” 

Inspired by an overheard conversation at a restaurant. A guy was basically complaining about people disgruntled with inflation, implying that it doesn’t really matter if you spend $300 at wholefoods or $500 for basic stuff. Like, get a life sort of attitude. Couldn’t resist….

Colon cancer, serious subject in life and not necessarily something to talk openly about. My work ‘Ode to rectal health’ was started a year ago when my dad was diagnosed with this condition. I also suffer from the same issues and those of you who follow my stories get to see my too frequent visits to doctors. 
During my recent show at @artmiamifairs at Aqua many ppl where shocked to hear more about this piece and started coming out with their own or their family members’ stories. 
Kirstie Alley is the most recent one among celebrities to succumb to this disease but there’s many more people who suffer from it or could prevent it if they had checked it up on time. 
I know it’s a difficult topic but what is art supposed to do other than make people think? Even it takes some shocking.

„Cain and Abel”
Oil on canvas, 63” x 63” (160 x 160cm), 2022 

Been painting it for too many months cause the topic is personal and unfortunately not something I’m unfamiliar with. The topic of sibling violence that unlike other forms of violence gets often downgraded to “a horseplay”. Story of my life, no actions taken, no defense, no consequences for my Cain. My heart is racing while I’m writing it, was even worse when I was painting it. It’s done, off my chest. I’m moving on. 

The painting is set in the Cain and Abel story, just moments before one kills the other, clenched fist and dark skies portend what’s about to happen. And one more thing. I portrayed God as a chicken, cause you really have to be one to choose one over another and be okay with what it’s gonna trigger.

@justynakisielewicz is a contemporary artist based in Miami, FL. Her paintings are aesthetically camp, cheeky, and lively with unexpected color combinations. She was dubbed the “pop culture obsessed, rebellious artist from Poland” and the “princess of pop culture” by Elle, an international fashion and lifestyle magazine.
 
 Originally from Poland, Justyna’s formative memories are shrouded in a monochrome hazes imilar to the brutalist architecture associated with communist rule. As a personal escape from the visual monotony of her surroundings, the artist enjoyed creating extravagant imagery with pigments and paper. She embellished what she saw; color served as a protective barrier from the gloom of everyday life.

 Several paintings by the artist are in the permanent collection of the National Museum in Gdansk, Poland. In 2018 Justyna was granted a Green Card for Individuals of Extraordinary Ability––also known as the Genius Visa––by the USA for being within the top 1% of her artistic field. She received a Master in Fine Arts from the Academy of Fine Arts in Warsaw, Poland with an emphasis in painting and textiles.

Veneer, 
Oil and gilding on wooden panel, 
24” x 24”/ 60 x 60cm 

From my “Icons” series featuring gold and silver leaf, this one was my response to the American culture of “being fine” whenever asked “how are you”. It presented a stark contrast to where I’m coming from and how in a very explicit way this question would get answered. Regardless of that there’s always something people hide, some true nature, feelings, traumas etc that long bottled up will inevitably resurface. In my case they resurfaced alright, with a bang, realigned some family ties, wiped out some people, but most of all brought me to a better place mentally and physically. That’s what I wish for y’all. 🫶

TVP Kultura on our show @galeria_test in Warsaw. 
Ania @anna_hlebowicz_art , the gallery curator talks about the concept to include the works of 12 female artists who learned their skills at the textile studio of Professor Dorota Grynczel at Academy of Fine Art in Warsaw.

Troche to potrwało! Szkic do tego obrazu zrobiłam w 2020 i odstawiłam na pozniej. Nie mogłam znaleźć dobrego sposobu jego realizacji. Dopiero w 2022, kiedy zaczęłam bawić sie w wycinanie drewna wymyśliłam ze to bedzie dobre medium. 
Samo drewno oprócz wycinania to dwa tygodnie przygotowywania, szlifowania, przeklejania, gruntowania. Wszystko to po to żeby panel nie deformował sie z czasem pod wpływem warunków atmosferycznych.  Malowanie to przy tym pestka. Najfajniejszą jednak częścią tej przygody są rozważania inżynierskie i rozwiązywanie problemów zawieszania, zasilania świateł itd. Nie lubię wystających kabli i to wymagało wymyślenia alternatywnych źródeł zasilania dla światła. No i wisienką na torcie jest to ze można z kanapy regulować światła pilotem. Co wy na to?

Die Freikörperkultur / FKK🧶🧵🪡

🧶 23” / 58.4 cm in diameter, cross stitch, crochet, embroidery, wool, acrylic, cotton yarn, glass beads; 

🧶 the body consists of 84 colors of threads and took 99.225 stitches to accomplish. 

🧶started in May 2022- finished in May 2023

Freikörperkultur is an attitude towards life, according to which the naked body is no reason for feelings of shame. The communally practiced nudity of the Freikörperkultur is often experienced in this sense as liberating and goes hand in hand with mutual acceptance and a positive body image.

With another show in the pipeline I’ve got to stretch this ☝️ not my favorite thing in the world as it’s really hard on your hands but I grew to appreciate the skill. My education was extremely conservative. We were taught to build all of our canvases from the scratch. It included stretching linen without any fancy tools (no staplers or pliers), only nails and hammers. We then cooked our own glue and ground. It was a work at its roots. Once my professor who taught us those techniques caught me in the art supply store buying the ready made canvas. She just shook her head with disappointment and said: “dear child, in art there is no cutting corners”. D’ya think so?

Polska Ludowa 
Embroidery and crochet on paper money, cotton, wool, hand dyed yarn, silk ribbons, sequins, gouache on paper
15” x 19”, 2023 

Polska Ludowa is an ambiguous term. It refers to a political system of communist regime (far from colorful and joyful) and folk art. This duplicity would get lost in translation hence the Polish title. For many those two meanings don’t bring good connotations at no surprise. The Soviet system, imposed on Poland, shackled the country. On the other hand, folk art or rather craft, was considered inferior to the real art. 
In my artistic practice I love to venture into ambiguity and let others have their interpretations. It adds to the conversation and usually it surprises me not to have thought about a work from this different perspective. So go ahead, lmk what is it for you and which character is your favorite. I’ll reveal that mine is Chopin dressed as a turoń.

“How to mend a broken heart”- is my upcoming embroidery. It’s been sketched out on a map which usually shows directions so it’s an interplay between being lost and trying to find your way out of despair. It’s also a personal story where I deal with some losses. While in Poland I had to bid farewell to my therapist who died prematurely and whom I miss. She was irreplaceable, an absolute power house. Then some indirect losses where I played a mere support to friends who lost their furry family. Anyone of you who have/had this experience or have a pet can possibly relate. I surely can. Finally it’s my way of dealing with some unfortunate family affairs and unsolvable shit that results in separation. 
It’s still long way before it’s finished but it’s all good, maybe when it’s done I’ll learn how to mend a broken heart.

How to mend a broken heart? 

For all of you out there who lost someone, something in you life. All those feeling of grief, sadness, anger, bargaining, reasoning. It’s a hard thing to live with. Personally, this past year has been full of goodbyes forever and farewells at the crossroads. 

On a technical note it’s an embroidery and painting on a paper map supported with material. The transparent bit of fabric is a bobbinet that resembles tulle but is made of cotton and is far more resistant than synthetic materials of that sort. Bobbinet is used by haute couture designers as a base for embroidering, lingerie or high quality bridal wear. 
Along with it I embroidered the majority of the work with silk threads that reflect light like nothing else. 

It was a meditation of sorts to deal with those emotions of loss and attempt to understand it. Can’t say I did grasp it nor accepted it but at least I did get some respite from all the thinking or crying. 

17” x 20” / 43 cm x 50.8 cm

Los Piratas 🏴‍☠️ 

Oil on canvas
60” x 60” / 152.4 x 152.4 cm 
2023 

Veni Vidi Vici - I came, I saw, I won - that could be a motto of conquistadors who colonized the New World. Perceived as Gods they were welcomed by the indigenous inhabitants. What happened next is illustrated in the background that was inspired by toile de jouy - a French “linen cloth” type of wallpaper that was also popular during the Colonial Era in the US. Colonization that I think about is not only about the land taken but also more current gentrification, globalization, religion wars and dominance. 
Coming from Poland - a land that was occupied, decimated and torn apart I see this matter as a bunch of influence imposed by the power. My recent trip to Mexico showed me a different kind of colonization where the conquest is still clashing with the indigenous spirit of its people. 
I tried to steer clear of moralism cause I just don’t know if all that happened back then and what happens now is good or bad. I guess is more complicated than that black and white categorization.

Przyszły rok zaczynam od otwarcia mojej pierwszej muzealnej indywidualnej wystawy pt „Keep the faith”. 
Zaprezentowanych bedzie moich 40 obrazow, w tym wiele z prywatnych kolekcji. Wspólnym mianownikiem bedzie temat wiary :
- katolickiej, w której sie urodziłam i wychowałam, a której nie wybrałam;
- we własne możliwości i moj American Dream (tu głownie z naciskiem na beznadziejna przyszłość absolwenta Akademii Sztuk Pięknych);
- konflikcie seksualnym a religii, czyli o grzechu jakim jest ciało i o wstydzie;
- alternatywy religijnej, czyli wiary w ideologie, sport, pieniądze. 

Ostatnia sala bedzie prezentować kilka tylko obrazow z pytaniem, w co Ty wierzysz? Chce zestawić ten obraz ze zdjecia, Jezusa, którego namalowałam w 2008 na ASP w Warszawie, ze świeżo namalowanym, juz tu w Ameryce, Virgin and Child (polski tytuł to Psia Bozia).
